Wait, I think I see the issue. Looking at how sections are built:

```tsx
const sections = useMemo<SectionInfo[]>(() => {
  const result: SectionInfo[] = [];
  const ungroupedPanels: PanelDescriptor[] = [];
  let globalPanelIndex = 0;
  let sectionIndex = 0;

  panels.forEach((item) => {
    if (isDashboardGroup(item)) {
      result.push({
        group: item,
        sectionIndex,
        panels: item.charts,
        globalPanelStartIndex: globalPanelIndex,
      });
      globalPanelIndex += item.charts.length;
      sectionIndex++;
    } else {
      ungroupedPanels.push(item);
    }
  });

  // If there are ungrouped panels, add them as the last section
  if (ungroupedPanels.length > 0) {
    result.push({
      group: null,
      sectionIndex,
      panels: ungroupedPanels,
      globalPanelStartIndex: ungroupedStartIndex,
    });
  }

  return result;
}, [panels]);
```

So section indices are 0, 1, 2, etc. And the bottom-most section would have the highest index.

The fact that only the bottom section works suggests that maybe the initialization effect is running and overwriting the state for the other sections, but not the last one?


The bottom section is likely the ungrouped one with `group: null`, which means when checking `section.group?.collapsed`, it returns `undefined` and defaults to `false` (expanded). For grouped sections above it, `section.group?.collapsed` might have a different value that's causing the collapse state to not work properly.

